<h2>
2) How APIs Work in JavaScript?
<p>The Key Concepts JavaScript uses a request-response model to work with web 
APIs. The most important technology for this is fetch(), which is a built-in 
function that allows you to make network requests. Here’s how it works:</p>
                            </h2>

                            <h2>3)how to use api
<p>JavaScript uses a request-response model
 to work with web APIs. The most important technology for this is fetch, which 
 is based on Promises and asynchronous programming
</p>
<p>1. The fetch() API (The Modern Way)
The fetch() function is built into modern browsers. It provides a logical
 way to fetch resources asynchronously across the network. It returns a
  Promise.</p>
 <p>2. Asynchronous Nature (Crucial!)
API calls are network operations. They take time—milliseconds or even seconds.
 JavaScript doesn't wait for them to finish (it's non-blocking). Instead, it 
 uses Promises and async/await to handle the response when it's ready, without
  freezing the webpage.</p>    
<p>3. HTTP Methods
The type of request you make is defined by its HTTP method:

GET: Retrieve data from the server (e.g., get a list of users).

POST: Send data to create a new resource (e.g., create a new user).

PUT/PATCH: Update an existing resource.

DELETE: Delete a resource.</p>

<p>4. Request and Response
Request: You send a request to a specific URL (the API endpoint). 
This request can contain headers (for authentication, content type) and a body
 (for sending data, like in a POST request).

Response: The server processes your request and sends back a response.
 This response includes:

Status Code: A number like 200 (OK), 201 (Created), 404 (Not Found), 500 
(Server Error).

Headers: Information about the response.

Body: The actual data you requested, usually in JSON format.
</p>
</h2>
